<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06061069 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06061069 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  STOCK; INVESTMENT; TRADE; REGULATION; OFFICIAL; GOVERNMENT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Richard G. Ketchum, one of the most influential regulators of the securitiesbusiness, will join the industry he helped oversee during his 14 years withthe government.;    Ketchum, the director of the division of market regulationat the Securities and Exchange Commission, plans to join the NationalAssociation of Securities Dealers, the self-regulatory organization thatoversees the NASDAQ stock trading system, on May 1.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  REGULATOR GETS OTC MART JOB  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     He will be executive vice president for legal, regulatory and marketpolicy, planning and review, a newly created position.;    In January, Ketchumwill assume the additional responsibilities of managing and operating thedealers association's office of general counsel, as well as the arbitration,corporate financing, investment companies and insurance affiliatesdepartments.;    Joseph Hardiman, president of the dealers association, saidthe job had been essentially created for Ketchum. Sounding like the generalmanager of a professional sports team, Hardiman said Ketchum's abilities weremore important than what position he would fill.;    &quot;When someone of hisstature and capabilities becomes available, you really look at the individualand not at a specific function in the organization,&quot; Hardiman said.&quot;Individuals of his stature don't become available very often.&quot;;    In aninterview Thursday, Ketchum, 40, said that he would take on a wide array ofissues in his new position. &quot;The responsibility for this job is to deal withpolicy issues, some of which deal with new products and new innovations,&quot; hesaid.;    Hardiman said that he expected to use Ketchum's experience toexplore possibilities for the NASD to expand into the markets for debtsecurities and derivatives, which are financial instruments that gain theirvalue from other securities.;    &quot;Rick brings a good deal of knowledge in bothof those markets,&quot; Hardiman said.;    At the SEC, Ketchum sought to increasecompetition among the nation's financial exchanges. He pushed for innovativetrading systems, including a privately owned computerized system forinstitutional investors, and for new types of securities, like indexparticipations, which allow exchanges to engage in so-called basket trading.;   Ketchum also oversaw the SEC's report on the stock market crash in 1987. Thereport provided some of the most detailed information about the circumstancessurrounding the crash.;    In the interview Thursday, Ketchum joked abouttaking a job in the industry he helped regulate, saying, &quot;Suddenly I see allthe arguments from the securities industry side, and now they make a lot moresense to me.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  New York Times  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910301  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  8D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  397  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday March 1, 199100061069,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>